comment.narrative:
As per Project Objective:

1. 0 ha of protected areas under a secure, and effectively managed, monitoring and enforcement regime; 
2. < 5,000 ha of high altitude grasslands (above 1,500m) in the Hissar-Alay and Vakhsh-Darvaz areas under a regulated and sustainable management regime;
3. < 2,000 ha of high altitude forest (above 1,500m) in the Hissar-Alay and Vakhsh-Darvaz areas under a sustainable management regime;
4. Primary snow leopard prey populations: Marco Polo Sheep (NT) – 1,125; Siberian Ibex (LC) – 4,190; Heptner’s markhor (EN) – 1,018;
5. Total snow leopard population in Tajikistan – 180-220;
6. None of individuals (and none of women as a proportion of the total) involved in, and directly benefiting from project investments in the conservation and sustainable use of snow leopard, snow leopard prey and snow leopard habitats. 

As per Project Outcomes: 

1.1. 2,777,018 ha of IUCN Category I and Category II protected areas;
1.2. Total annual budget allocation for the management of IUCN Category I – IV protected areas is US$250,000/annum;
1.3. METT scores for: Tajik NP (Jirgital section) – 20; and for Tajik NP (Tavildara section, including Sangvor) – 20.
1.4. 10 active patrol rangers in Jirgital and 8 active patrol rangers in Tavildara (including Sangvor) sections of Tajik NP;
1.5. 15% of total area of Jirgital and 12% of Tavildara (including Sangvor) sections of Tajik NP under a secure and effective monitoring and enforcement regime;
1.6. >15 of poaching (of snow leopard and prey); and >45 of other illegal (encroachments for crops and grazing, wood harvesting) incidents recorded (and prosecuted – 1 and 2 respectively) per annum by ranger patrol staff from the Jirgital and Tavildara sections of Tajik NP;
1.7. <100 individuals (<15 out of which women) from targeted villages directly involved in, and <10 individuals (1-2 of which women) financially benefiting from the management of the Jirgital and Tavildara sections of Tajik NP.  

