1.1 The total area of protected areas falling under IUCN Category I and II is 2837018 ha.
1.2 The total annual budget allocated for the management of protected areas under IUCN Categories I to IV is $450,000 per year.
1.3 METT scores for Sangvor branch of TNP are 40 and for Lyakhsh branch of TNP is 44.
1.4. The number of active rangers in TNP Sangvor branch is 16 and in TNP Lyakhsh branch is 18.
1.5 More than 85% of Lyakhsh and more than 60% of Sangvor TNP sections (including Sangvor reserve) are under safe and effective monitoring and enforcement regime.
1.6 At least 2,000 people, including 1,100 women, are involved in the project areas and at least 150 people, including 80 women, benefit financially from working together with the administration of Lyakhsh and Sangvor sections of TNP.
2.1 An overview of the status of days of grazing (spring/autumn and summer) in the high mountain pastures of Hissar-Alay and Vakhsh-Darvaz is prepared and submitted to the project Steering Committee;
2.2 The productivity of highland pastures of Hissar-Alay and Vakhsh-Darvaz has reached 1 ton/ha;
2.3. 50% increase in the average grass cover per hectare from the total grass cover was achieved in eatable and edible species for ungulates and cattle in Hissar-Alay and Vakhsh-Darvaz high altitude pastures;
2.4 At least 7 Pasture User Unions have approved pasture management plans and are implementing them in the pastures of Hissar-Alay and Vakhsh-Darvaz;
2.5. At least 14 households in Hissar-Alay and Vakhsh-Darvaz directly benefited from technical and grant support of the project, through implementation of sustainable pasture management practices (7 households), introduction of alternative fuel and energy technology (7 households);
2.6 At least 4,000 ha of degraded pastures and at least 2,000 ha of degraded forests of Hissar-Alay and Vakhsh Darvaz are in the state of active rehabilitation and restoration;
2.7. At least 3 Participatory Forest Management committees (PFMC) are involved in planning, management and monitoring of highland forests of Hissar-Alay and Vakhsh Darvaz;
2.8. At least 100 persons per year are involved in wildlife monitoring program through training on law enforcement and refresher course.
3.1 The concept of SLIMs for monitoring high mountain ecosystems and tools for its application in the Republic of Tajikistan developed
3.2 At least 2 meetings of the National Committee for Snow Leopard Conservation held
3.3. Action Plan of the Republic of Tajikistan is updated and at least 3 of its programmes are being implemented.
3.4. Agreement of Central Asian countries on snow leopard ecosystem conservation signed and declaration on cooperation with partners/countries of the region developed.
3.5 Knowledge resources on snow leopard and project achievements are demonstrated at least at 6 international and national events.
3.6 Monitoring activities cover 25% of snow leopard range and 20% of its prey area.

1.1. Extent of IUCN Category I and Category II protected areas increased to 365 thous. ha;
